children":[{"type":"admonitionTitle","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Note","key":"QsLSpysMX5"}],"key":"umuKMgfMGX"},{"type":"code","lang":"","value":"**Did I Get This?**\n\n*(Interactive activity — available in the OLI platform)*","position":{"start":{"line":36,"column":1},"end":{"line":38,"column":1}},"key":"QuEBmA84ae"}],"key":"HXzt0xTkGa"},{"type":"admonition","kind":"note","children":[{"type":"admonitionTitle","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Note","key":"Ajnn2DHD4e"}],"key":"Zlfpcf33gY"},{"type":"code","lang":"","value":"**Did I Get This?**\n\n*(Interactive activity — available in the OLI platform)*","position":{"start":{"line":42,"column":1},"end":{"line":44,"column":1}},"key":"SldGvCHEOr"}],"key":"QOagbioitu"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":47,"column":1},"end":{"line":47,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"At this point, we have a good sense of what happens as we take random samples from a population. Our simulation suggests that our initial intuition about the shape and center of the sampling distribution is correct. If the population has a proportion of p, then random samples of the same size drawn from the population will have sample proportions close to p. More specifically, the distribution of sample proportions will have a mean of p. We also observed that for this situation, the sample proportions are approximately normal. We will see later that this is not always the case. But if sample proportions are normally distributed, then the distribution is centered at p. Now we want to use simulation to help us think more about the variability we expect to see in the sample proportions. Our intuition tells us that larger samples will better approximate the population, so we might expect less variability in large samples. In the next walk-through we will use simulations to investigate this idea. After that walk-through, we will tie these ideas to more formal theory.","position":{"start":{"line":47,"column":1},"end":{"line":47,"column":1}},"key":"g5sZUBgMoD"}],"key":"MnQSM6QLKG"},{"type":"admonition","kind":"note","children":[{"type":"admonitionTitle","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Video","position":{"start":{"line":49,"column":1},"end":{"line":49,"column":1}},"key":"aQy90MVjoz"}],"key":"yCKEcuOEkr"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":50,"column":1},"end":{"line":50,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"link","url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tUvXeJ3A3_s","position":{"start":{"line":50,"column":1},"end":{"line":50,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Behavior of Sample Proportion 2","position":{"start":{"line":50,"column":1},"end":{"line":50,"column":1}},"key":"sIkVKDKsTx"}],"urlSource":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tUvXeJ3A3_s","key":"ndq9K0CPgR"}],"key":"T2LySBcWF2"}],"key":"zvc3QuaeWn"},{"type":"admonition","kind":"note","children":[{"type":"admonitionTitle","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Note","key":"cHv2IQZWYf"}],"key":"LwUmjMoT5L"},{"type":"code","lang":"","value":"**Did I Get This?**\n\n*(Interactive activity — available in the OLI platform)*","position":{"start":{"line":54,"column":1},"end":{"line":56,"column":1}},"key":"R6Mou6R4LE"}],"key":"mtzjnSKZ2S"}],"key":"hqWzHjwlmW"}],"key":"WS4VvKdHyH"},"references":{"cite":{"order":[],"data":{}}},"footer":{"navigation":{"prev":{"title":"Parameters vs. Statistics","url":"/pages/m12-parameters-vs-statistics","group":"Unit 4: Probability"},"next":{"title":"Behavior of Sample Proportion (2 of 3)","url":"/pages/m12-behavior-of-sample-proportion-2-of-3","group":"Unit 4: Probability"}}},"domain":"http://localhost:3001"}